pdc_describe.title: Top right menu pull down doesn't work at times

comments.body: @hectorcorrea This problem rings a bell — I feel like we had another app with a similar problem with the ".com" or other domain getting interpreted as a format suffix. Does it work if you URL-encode the address to `guest-user@gmail%2Ecom`?

I suspect that the application is erroneously adding `@princeton.edu` to e-mail addresses when e-mail addresses already feature a different domain name for the user.

When testing this error within the `staging` environment, I found the following:

```bash
irb(main):004:0> User.find_by(email: "ppplpdctest@gmail.com")
=> nil
irb(main):005:0> User.find_by(email: "ppplpdctest@gmail.com@princeton.edu")
=> #<User id: 150, email: "ppplpdctest@gmail.com@princeton.edu", created_at: "2023-02-17 13:32:55.903253000 -0500", updated_at: "2023-02-17 13:32:55.903253000 -0500", provider: "cas", uid: "ppplpdctest@gmail.com", orcid: nil, default_collection_id: 1, display_name: "Leslie", full_name: "Leslie Smith", family_name: "Smith", email_messages_enabled: true>
```

The code where the error is triggered seems to be here: https://github.com/pulibrary/pdc_describe/blob/main/app/controllers/users_controller.rb#L55-L58

```
def set_user
  @user = User.friendly.find(params[:id])
  redirect_to action: action_name, id: @user.friendly_id, status: :moved_permanently unless @user.friendly_id == params[:id]
end
```
Turns out a playbook has to be on the main branch before you can create a Template in Tower based on it. So I'm going to merge this tonight so we have a template to start next steps on tomorrow.

The oawaiver role is now failing CI on the main branch, but the failure is an idempotence failure. Not sure if it's related. The test run is here:
https://github.com/pulibrary/princeton_ansible/actions/runs/4198847185/jobs/7283000031 
and the 'changed' tasks include:

tiger-data-app.title: Copy and paste write_version task as suggested by rails-template
Create a basic layout using bootstrap

comments.body:
Confirmed in the meeting this morning that this can go ahead. Should wait for the vite PR to avoid merge conflicts:

- #39

I thought I'd share a couple of thoughts and questions about how this would work:

1. To what extent would Rails controllers fulfill the role of the API (i.e., the views would constitute the UI)? Would scrupulously creating controller endpoints for any data that controllers or views/helpers fill the gaps?
2. I've seen token-based auth folded into controllers so browsers and automated clients use the same endpoints, but I think it's more common to have different endpoints.
3. One of the ramifications of having a significant external command-line/API customer base that Matt, Kate, and I discussed recently is that any backwards-incompatible changes would potentially break their integrations. Maybe this argues against considering Rails controllers the API?
4. What are the best practices for having a separate, versioned API?
5. I'm not sure that having a "Middle Layer" between the UI/API and the backend is a requirement, or if it's one possible approach to making sure that users don't have unmediated access to MediaFlux just because they are using a command-line tool or API integration. Basically, maybe this app is the "Middle Layer"?

Notes from this morning:

> Bess: would like to have a separate design session, with concrete use cases.
> Esme’s concerns about upgrade path are important
> Kate: Talking with Matt, would like to get concrete usecases
> Hector: Would like to start as simply as possible. We probably won’t have enough information for the next few months. If we start wrong it could be a pain to maintain
> Bess: We don’t have solid requirements right now… we’ll probably need to rewrite it.
> Carolyn: Controller is the api
> Close this PR: Make a new one where it’s in the controller

I had more questions in the meeting this morning:

>  If the license key is baked into the image, and the image is only accessible within the Princeton network, can we document that in the README, or is it important to keep even that much secret?
> These images are only good until March… start/end? If they work, can we agree just to stay with that, and have an assurance that we’ll get a fresh baked image every couple months? Or is it important to move to Java?
> Testing will be particularly reliant on mocking the MF interface… unless we want to pull that mocking down, so it’s the wrapper that gets mocked.

Conclusion was that we'll know more after the meetings next week:

> This is an open question – but this comes done to our decision as a team. Would like to know more about why he recommends the Java environment.

No other immediate action
